{"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "schema", "document", "Document"], "kwargs": {"metadata": {"doc_id": "97b48ece-e5e5-4449-8c75-209f93fdfb1f", "source": "NexaCorp Policy Handbook v5.2", "part": "3. Human Resources Policies", "section": "3.9 Attendance, Timekeeping & Conduct", "subsection": "3.9.3 Dress Code & Professional Appearance", "raw_content": "NexaCorp maintains a business casual dress code in its offices, with the expectation that employees will dress more formally when meeting clients, attending industry events, or representing NexaCorp at external forums. 'Business casual' is defined as neat, professional attire that is free from offensive graphics, slogans, or excessive informality. Jeans are permitted on Fridays ('NexaFriday') and during designated team events. Specific client-facing roles may have elevated dress code requirements communicated through the relevant Business Unit. PART IV \u2014 ANTI-HARASSMENT, DISCRIMINATION & EQUAL OPPORTUNITY", "type": "text", "text": "Part: 3. Human Resources Policies\n            Section: 3.9 Attendance, Timekeeping & Conduct\n            Subsection: 3.9.3 Dress Code & Professional Appearance\n            NexaCorp maintains a business casual dress code in its offices, with the expectation that employees will dress more formally when meeting clients, attending industry events, or representing NexaCorp at external forums. 'Business casual' is defined as neat, professional attire that is free from offensive graphics, slogans, or excessive informality. Jeans are permitted on Fridays ('NexaFriday') and during designated team events. Specific client-facing roles may have elevated dress code requirements communicated through the relevant Business Unit. PART IV \u2014 ANTI-HARASSMENT, DISCRIMINATION & EQUAL OPPORTUNITY"}, "page_content": "Part: 3. Human Resources Policies\n            Section: 3.9 Attendance, Timekeeping & Conduct\n            Subsection: 3.9.3 Dress Code & Professional Appearance\n            NexaCorp maintains a business casual dress code in its offices, with the expectation that employees will dress more formally when meeting clients, attending industry events, or representing NexaCorp at external forums. 'Business casual' is defined as neat, professional attire that is free from offensive graphics, slogans, or excessive informality. Jeans are permitted on Fridays ('NexaFriday') and during designated team events. Specific client-facing roles may have elevated dress code requirements communicated through the relevant Business Unit. PART IV \u2014 ANTI-HARASSMENT, DISCRIMINATION & EQUAL OPPORTUNITY", "type": "Document"}}